author: rooneg
msg: * subversion/bindings/ruby/client.c
(cl_log_message_func): new callback function to pass log messages into client
functions that require them.
(cl_get_parse_arg, cl_put_parse_arg): deleted.  they have no purpose now that
the client functions no longer use editor's.  at some point, we will need to
recreate this functionality (since there is currently no way to receive
notifications during an action), but for now it can go away.
(cl_status): if 0'd out because it depends on code in wc.c, which does not
build yet.
(svn_ruby_init_client): commented out the rb_define_method for cl_status.
(all other functions): bring up to date with regard to the arguments the
svn functions now take.  mostly this means changing from svn_stringbuf_t's
to const char *'s, removing arguments related to xml files, putting in
log message callbacks and batons, getting rid of the editors that used to
wrap some functions, and adding new arguments that have been added since
these were last updated.

author: dlr
msg: * subversion/bindings/swig/svn_types.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/svn_string.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/svn_fs.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/swigutil_java.c
* subversion/bindings/swig/svn_client.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/swigutil_java.h
* subversion/bindings/swig/util.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/svn_repos.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/svn_delta.i
* subversion/bindings/swig/apr.i
Added initial experimentation with SWIG/Java, the results of
straight porting from the SWIG/Python bindings of several months
back.  These bindings should be expected to not interfere with the
existing SWIG bindings for other languages (e.g. Python, Ruby,
etc.), to swig successfully, and not to compile.  This should be
treated as a brain dump and very raw examples, not as usable code!
Other than obvious things like compiler errors, out of date code,
and incorrect type mappings/names between C and Java types, open
issues include the need for a consistent contract for the handling
of Java object allocation in JNI code, and how JNI types like jclass
and jmethodID require JNI reference decrementing.  Also todo is to
pillage xela's ancient hand-coded Java bindings for usable code and
examples.
